On February 3, 2022, At 0708 ET , XPO Logistics XMP notified ERTS of a Cargo release at XMP. It was reported that 1-quart  released of UN 1993 "Diesel Fuel No 2" from a 250-gallon tote due to a small hole being punctured in the bottom left from a forklift puncture, impacting the trailer floor. The tote is currently on the dock, and the terminal has tried to stop the release with a small piece of cardboard and absorbents to no avail. ERTS dispatched Rock Leaf Environmental LLC to conduct all onsite cleanup operations. At 0810 Rock Leaf personnel arrived onsite and confirmed approximately 2qt of product released to a 4ft by 4ft area of the concrete dock floor and a 6ft by 6ft area inside the trailer. The damaged tote was cut up and absorbents were worked into the impacted areas and collected into a 55-gallon metal drum.  All waste was staged onsite for terminal personnel to manage.

On February 4, 2022, facility personnel at the above-referenced R+L Carriers (RLC) location discovered approximately one (1) gallon of methanol released from one (1) damaged 5-gallon pail following a mid-transit load shift. RLC retained Cura Emergency Services, LC (CES), who dispatched a crew from First Call Environmental, LLC (FCE) to perform the necessary corrective action. FCE personnel drummed the damaged pail, then utilized absorbents and hand tools to remediate the impacted surface.

Ward Trucking released a hazardous, UN1993, 3, tote release. Approximately 85% of a 275-gallon poly tote has been punctured by a forklift resulting in the release to impact the trailer and the ground below. Terminal personnel have secured the release with various absorbents at this time. AT 1159 ET, Sustain, LLC dispatched EnviroServe to conduct initial cleanup and remedial activities. The contractor indicated that the release spread throughout the parking lot into a snowbank that leads to runoff drain that may lead to a waterway. The contractor indicated that approximately 30-gallons is left inside the tote. Due to the rain and the product spreading from the rain, additional manpower was requested. The product has been identified as AFS AWDA-3000. The contractor is placing absorbents down in the drain to stop the release from spreading and applying additional absorbents to the parking lot. The contractor utilized a PID meter near the impacted soil by the drain and the reading came back hot. The contractor covered the area with plastic sheeting for future remediation. Cleanup is complete pending the remediation. Contractor has generated (18) 55-gallon drums of impacted absorbent materials and (2) drums of product impacted with water for waste pending future disposition.
THE RESPONDER WENT TO THE SPILL, AND CLEAN UP THE SPILL.

column169: The pin-hole puncture in the bottom of the drum appeared to have been caused due to a nail head protruding from the pallet the drum was on. column168: On 2-6-2022 at 1400 personnel in the CSXT Gentilly Yard discovered ACFX 71254, a loaded tank  car of Methyl Methacrylate leaking from top of the tank car. The car was isolated and Roehm  America LLC were notified (CHEMTREC Report #2022020600039). SPSI, a CSXT response  contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found the vapors were being released from the  top of the tank car.  The liquid line valve was leaking from the threads where it threaded on to  the tank car. The issue identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shipper  Martin Hutton with Roehm America at 973-440-7558. Contractor personnel used a wrench to  tighten the valve and stopped the leak.  The leak was secured and the car will require an  approved OTMA prior to being released for transport. This incident did not require a special  switching move.

column168: PACKAGE CAME DOWN SMALL SORT SLIDE TO SORTING AREA. SORTER NOTICED WET CARDBOARD, SHUT THE BELT OFF, AND NOTIFIED MANAGEMENT. MANAGEMENT INFORMED DMP. FIRST RESPONDER COLLECTED PACKAGE, NO NOTABLE LEAKAGE ON BELT. PACKAGE BROUGHT TO DMP CAGE, OPENED PACKAGE, FOUND CONTENTS WERE FLAMMABLE LIQUID. CAP HAD TAPE APPLIED TO IT AROUND THE CIRCUMFERENCE, BUT TAPE HAD COME OFF APPROXIMATELY HALF WAY. NO DAMAGE NOTED TO INTERNAL CONTAINER, SO THE SOURCE OF LEAK WAS DETERMINED TO BE THE CAP. WHETHER NOT PUT ON TIGHTLY ENOUGH, OR NOT DESIGNED TO SECURE TIGHTLY IS UNKNOWN.

column168: SequenceEvent: Plastic Pail was found by Package handler in the outbound by door 108. According to him it was wet and leaking. DurationRel: 1 and MitigateEffect: the spill was small and only leaked on the pail itself, and the cart is was sitting on. what did leak out was cleaned by QA.

column168: A Veolia field technician picked up a pallet from the shipper containing the 95 gallon over pack on 2/14/2022. There were not obvious issues with the pallet or container at the time of pick up. The pallet was safely loaded on our box truck and transported to Veolia's 10 day intransit facility located in  Poca, WV. After arriving at our facility the Veolia employee attempted to offload the pallet from the truck. As he removed the pallet, a board on the pallet broke causing the 95 gallon over pack to shift and fall to the floor below. When the 95 gallon over pack hit the ground the lid loosened allowing some of the liquid contents to spill onto the warehouse floor. Veolia is unsure if the container's lid was loose upon pick up or if the lid came loose as a result of the impact with the ground. Either way the lid was compromised in the fall which led to the spill. The initial spill was limited to the time it took our employee to get off the forklift and pick the container up. Our employee was able to use booms and floor dry to mitigate the effects of the release. Once contained he used spill pads and floor dry to absorb the liquid material. All spill debris was properly cleaned up and placed inside a spill clean up drum for proper disposal.
column169: The lesson learned from this release is that Veolia needs to have a conversation with our customer and our employees. The customer should not classify a drum as a solid material if it contains a large amount of liquid. The customer should also properly secure any container before offering it up for shipment. In terms of Veolia employees, our team should always verify each lid to ensure it is properly closed. Veolia will have a meeting with the employee to discuss the incident and review the lessons learned with the employee. We will highlight the importance of double checking each container prior to transportation and we will also highlight the importance of checking pallet integrity before leaving a customers site.

column58: Pressure Relief Valve or Device - Reclosing
column168: On 2/3/2022 at approx. 07:39, the IAPX 1064 was found to be excessively venting while in the Vancouver railyard.  The area was immediately isolated and a Hazmat contractor was called to inspect the car.  It was found that the car was venting through the safety relief valve due to excess pressure.  The car was vented down to a level below the regulating valve pressure.  The pressure quickly rose again indicating an issue with the insulative properties of the car.  The car was vented in a controlled manner periodically until trucks were able to offload the remaining product and the car was vented down to 0 psi.  Release estimates are approximate based upon recovered liquid argon into trucks.  All Argon dissipated to atmosphere.  The empty car will move to shop under an OTMA that Airgas has applied for.  Airgas will conduct an investigation once the car arrives to shop.
NO COMMENTS PROVIDED.

column168: THERE WAS A PACKAGE JAM ON THE S1/1-TC3 ELT. THE JAM CAUSED A PACKAGE TO BECOME DAMAGED AND SPILL THE CONTENTS ALL OVER THE BELT AND ONTO THE MOTOR STARTER RIGHT BELOW. ONCE THE LIQUID CONTENTS SPILLED ONTO THE STARTER,IT COMBINED WITH A SPARK TO CAUSE A FIRE ON THE COVER OF THE STARTER. IN THE AREA TO MAKE SURE NO FURTHER DAMAGE HAD OCCURRED. THE WIRING AND COMPONENTS INSIDE THE MOTOR STARTER WAS NOT DAMAGED. THE EXTERIOR COVER WAS THE PART THAT WAS CAUGHT ON FIRE BUT IT DID NOT GAIN NO FURTHER HARM.

AT 1205 I RECEIVED A CALL FROM A SUPERVISOR. HE INDICATED THAT A DRIVER HAD A HAZMAT PACKAGE BREAK OPEN ON-SITE. AFTER HE PULLED IT OUT OF THE TRAILER THE BOTTOM FELL OUT AND AND ONE BOTTLE FELL TO THE GROUND AND BROKE, CAUSING VAPORS TO FORM. I GOT A 2021 DECISION TREE, PPE, AND SPILL TRAYS FROM THE DMP AND HEADED TO THE DROP-OFF LOCATION. IN THE MEANTIME BECAUSE OF THE VAPORS CAUSING IMMEDIATE CONCERN, THE DRIVER CALLED 911. THE WEST CHICAGO FD RESPONDED AND CLEANED UP THE SPILLED MATERIAL. THE COMPANY KEPT THE 5 INTACT BOTTLES. I CONTAINERIZED THE CARDBOARD AND BROUGHT IT BACK TO ADDISON DMP. THEY WILL DISPOSE OF SPILL MATERIAL.

column168: (55)gal metal drum arrived crushed and leaking, terminal uploaded pictures showing it was crushed but it started leaking in transit. Drum loaded loose on the floor up against another drum, possibly a hole was rubbed into it in transit or may have been previous damage. About (40)gal released which evaporated in transit. Terminal put down absorbents and over-packed into a salvage drum for proper disposal.
column169: Provide more training to personnel on safe handling procedures of hazmat and proper techniques for protecting freight for transit.

column168: On 2/22/2022 a Veolia employee was loading drums into a trailer at the Veolia, Schenecady, NY facility when the employee inadvertently punctured a 55 gallon metal drum on the trailer being loaded. The employee realized the leak right away due to the strong solvent smell. The employee may have been rushing to complete using the forklift due to forklift training being scheduled for new employees. The drum was placed immediately on its side to prevent it from leaking further and then was overpacked into an 851A2 salvage drum to continue transportation to the ultimate disposal facility.     The drum leaked about 10 gallons of mixed solvents after being struck by the forklift. The liquid was cleaned up with spill pads and absorbent and the drum was over-packed into an appropriate 85 gallon salvage drum along with the clean up materials. The duration of release is anticipated to be about 5 minutes no more than 10 gallons leaking.
column169: On 2/22/2022 the Veolia safety manager was notified and performed an investigation of the incident. The results of the investigation is that the employee was rushing. The trailer was being filled with other containers and the employee was not immediately aware that they had struck a drum behind a pallet. Human error did have a role in this incident. The employee was removed from forklift and will be retrained.

FULLY LABELED HAZ-MAT SHIPMENT WAS VISUALLY DISCOVERED WET IN APPEARANCE AND EMITTING A SOUR ODOR BY AN UNLOADER IN SECTION-E. WITHOUT TOUCHING THE PKG HE EVACUATED THE AREA AND NOTIFIED HIS IMMEDIATE SUPERVISOR. DMP WAS CONTACTED AND WITHIN 1 MINUTE A RESPONDER ARRIVED, DONNING THE PROPER PPE. AFTER FOLLOWING THE DECISION TREE   APPROPRIATE RESPONSE SHEET, THE DAMAGE WAS CONTAINED (NO SPILLAGE OUTSIDE OF CARTON), THEN TRANSPORTED TO THE DMP PROCESSING AREA. CLOSER INSPECTION REVEALED THAT THE NECKS ON 2 OF 4 PLASTIC 1-GAL JUGS WERE SLIGHTLY BENT, CREATING BREACHES THAT CAUSED APPROX. 10 OUNCES OF THE LIQUID TO LEAK THROUGH AND INTO A SIDE WALL AND BOTTOM OF THE CARTON. ALTHOUGH IT APPEARED TOO MUCH WEIGHT WAS PLACED ON TOP OF THE PARCEL, THERE WAS NO INTERNAL PACKING MATERIAL. THE OUTER CARTON WAS A DOUBLEWALL FIBERBOARD BOX, RATED AT A 51 LBS/IN EDGE CRUSH TEST (ECT).

RESPONDER RESPONDED TO A LEAKING PACKAGE IN THE UNLOAD WITH FULL PPE ON. USING THE DECISION TREE THE RESPONDER CLEANED UP THE LEAKING PACKAGE PLACING ALL MATERIAL IN A LINED SPILL TUB. THE RESPONDER TRANSPORTED THE MATERIAL TO DMP FOR FURTHER PROCESSING. UPON ARRIVAL I NOTED THAT ONE 1 GALLON BOTTLE HAD A LOOSE CAP AND LEAKED ON THE OTHER THREE BOTTLES. ALL MATERIAL WAS DISPOSED OF THOUGH DMP.
NO COMMENTS PROVIDED.

column168: I RESPONDED TO A CALL FOR A LEAKING HAZMAT IN THE WEST SORT AISLE, ACROSS FROM DOOR 18, AT 12:36. AFTER ARRIVING AT THE LOCATION I FOUND THAT THE LEAKING HAZMAT (CLASS 8) HAD ALREADY BEEN REMOVED FROM THE BELT AND BROUGHT UP TO THE CATWALK. I BROUGHT THE PACKAGE BACK TO THE PSC FOR PROCESSING AND REPORTED TO THE DAY SORT RMP, THAT THE LEAKING HAZMAT HAD BEEN MOVED BEFORE I ARRIVED. REACHED OUT TO THE FULL-TIME RMP, TO ADDRESS THE ISSUE. FOLLOWING THIS, I INSPECTED THE CONTENTS OF THE PACKAGE TO FIND THAT ONE OF THE BOTTLES APPEARED TO HAVE A FAULTY CLOSURE/LID: LIQUID WAS LEAKING OUT OF THE BOTTLE WHEN THE BOTTLE WAS EITHER NOT UPRIGHT OR SLIGHT PRESSURE WAS PUT ON THE BOTTLE. THE SECOND BOTTLE HAD BEEN LEAKED ON BY THE FIRST BOTTLE BUT WAS NOT ITSELF LEAKING. ALL CONTENTS WERE DAMAGED AND PROCESSED THROUGH THE DMP.

column168: awb 9175-8111 was tendered as a pallet shipment 1pc @ 306 # freighter only contents Hardware on February  15th 1215pm    Sunday shift usually includes Ramp agents cleaning up staging areas for each destination and trying to locate and move older awb's. Ramp agent Ryan noticed a red box saying Tite Foam on the bottom of a pallet it looked familiar the top half of the pallet had black plastic over it held to the pallet with clear shrink wrap. After removing the wrap to verify what the contents of the shipment was he notified the CSA lead on shift of the problem. There was 17 small boxes under the covering when moving them to verify what was what all the of the all surface limited quantity labels were facing inward and not visible from any outside views. I physical searched the whole shipment opening each box that was on the pallet. I found 13 boxes containing undeclared hazmat 4 boxes containing Hardware as the awb was declared.
NO COMMENTS PROVIDED.

SequenceEvent: The hazmat was leaking inside of the back of the van, when the driver got back the hazmat was placed inside a black tote and then placed inside of the hazmat cage. column168: 02/28/22 at 00:57 hours, It was reported to H/M Scoons that in Syracuse Yard QC285 terminal personnel had discovered TILX304958, a Loaded tank car of Liquefied Petroleum Gas, leaking from the protective housing area. The car was isolated and AUX Sable Liquid Products, NYS DEC and NRCwere notified. (CHEMTREC 2022-02-28-00002. Enviroserve a CSX contractor responded and found the tank car was leaking from the protective housing area. Upon claiming the railcar and accessing the protective housing it was fond that the liquid line valve was open and the secondary securement plug was improperly installed. The issue was identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shipper Brad Brancato 851-715-0642 brad.brancato@auxsable.com.    Enviroserve personnel corrected the defects and secured the leak. Railcar car was released to transportation. This incident did not require a special switching move. 7.1.

column168: Driver was traveling on a 4 lane highway. A 3rd party struck the Clean Harbors truck at a high rate of speed causing the truck off the road to the right, striking a guard rail. The truck broke through the rail, down an embankment and into trees. While the driver was able to control the truck, and keep it from rolling over, the trailer struck the trees causing it to split open and lose most the load of 82 drums. 28 of the drums broke open and released their contents onto the ground and surrounding trees and foliage. The drums that were opened, were rated for the material, and closed to manufacturer's specifications. EMS, and police were dispatched. A field service crew from clean harbors was dispatched for clean up. A third party clean up crew was also called in by the police on the scene. The crew put all the damaged drums into salvage drums, and prepared them for shipping. All the contaminated soil and foliage was removed and put into a roll off container for proper disposal. All the absorbent material that was used was also disposed of. At this time clean up is on going as soil testing is completed.

column168: At 10:19 ET, Landstar notified ERTS of a cargo release of ACPC12261B (UN1294).  The release impacted the flat bed trailer #649018 and no storm drains or waterways were impacted by the release. ERTS dispatched Allied International Emergency (AIE) to respond and confirm amount release and size of impacted area.  At 1255 ET,  AIE arrived on site and confirmed the material was leaking from where the 90-degree elbow threads onto the bottom of the tote and it impacted a 1' x 1' area of the the trailer floor. AIE advised they have completed the clean-up. They used pads and clay-based absorbents to collect the released material. One drum of waste was generated and pending disposal at the time of document preparation.

column168: On 2-23-2022 at 0900 hrs., I John Vergis Hazardous Materials Officer for the WLE, was called about tank car GATX 63064 with a possible leak at our Collins, OH rail yard.  The WLE car inspector in our Hartland Yard in Collins, said that he could smell an odor and that the protective housing on the top the car was frosted over.  I went to Collins to look at the car.  I removed seal number 4835364 from the protective housing lid and found that both the liquid valves were leaking.  The valve handles were tight but I tried to tighten them a little more, which I was able to do so.  The valves all had nylon zip ties through the valve handle to keep them from being opened.  I had to remove them in order to get the valve handles to turn.  I could not get the liquid valve on the B end of the car to stop leaking even though it was shut properly.  I checked the valve plugs and found that they were loose.  I tightened the plus on both liquid valves and the vapor valve.  They were all loose.  Tightening the plugs on the liquid valves were the only way I could get them to stop leaking.  I had the cars brought to the main WLE rail yard in Brewster where I had the car owner come look at it.  The shipper obtained a movement approval from Collins, OH to Brewster, OH. They sent Enviroserve out to flare the car down in Brewster but found that there was a 200 gallon heal on the car so it could not be flared.  They did check to see if the valves were leaking and they said they were not.  They checked the pressure on the car and it was only 18 pounds.  They then came back with the proper equipment to do a proper test on the car with a pressure of 50 pounds.  They said that they could not get any of the valves to leak and when they took the plugs out of the valves, they looked good on the inside.  This car was approved for transportation by Enviroserve.  Perhaps the valves had ice inside them from leaking and maybe that's why they didn't seal.  I do not know.  This car was put back into service on 3-7-2022.  NARRI: 5(4+5+0)x(2+0)=90

column168: DRIVER LOADED UN1263, WASTE PAINT RELATED MATERIAL, CLASS 3 ONTO A TRIPLE DOME LID SINGLE COMPARTMENT VACUUM TANK TRAILER. THE REAR DOME LID WAS NOT PROPERLY SECURED BEFORE MOVEMENT OF THE VEHICLE. WHEN TRUCK WAS LEAVING THE PLANT AND TURNING ONTO THE STREET, THE PAINT RELATED MATERIAL SPILLED FROM THE REAR DOME LID ONTO THE STREET AND GROUND. THE TRUCK HAD ONLY TRAVELED APPROXIMATELY 1/2 MILE WHEN HE DISCOVERED THE SPILL FROM THE REAR DOME LID OF THE TRAILER. THE DRIVER PULLED OFF OF THE ROAD AND PARKED. LOCAL AUTHORITIES WERE NOTIFIED. THE POLICE AND FIRE DEPARTMENT RESPONDED. AN ENVIROMENTAL CREW WAS ALSO DISPATCHED TO THE SCENE FOR RESPONSE AND PROPER CLEAN UP AND REMEDIATION. THE SITE CLEAN UP AND REMEDIATION IS COMPLETE. WASTE GENERATED FROM THE SPILL IS AWAITING DISPOSAL. THE REMAINDER OF THE LOAD WAS DELIVERED AS PLANNED.

column168: XPO Logistics Terminal XAB reported a 50-gallons of UN3463 "Propionic Acid FG" released on the trailer floor and yard from a 2265-pound plastic tote that was punctured due to improper loading. ERTS dispatched HEPACO to conduct all onsite cleanup operations. At 0800 ET HEPACO personnel arrived onsite and confirmed approximately 15-gallons of product released to a 5'x5' area of the trailer floor and a10'x10' area of concrete. HEPACO transferred the nonimpacted product into a new tote. The damaged tote was cut up and acid gator was utilized to neutralize the impacted areas, then swept up into two 55-gallon plastic drums. All waste was staged on site for terminal personnel to manage.

During the loading of freight at the destination terminal the drum was punctured by a protruding piece of metal sticking out of another skid. The drum was immediately turned on it's side to prevent further release. The released material was collected using absorbent pads and placed into an overpack for disposal. The damaged drum was then placed into an overpack to await disposition from the customer. Due to the drum being placed into the overpack, the packaging specs were not able to be safely obtained.
column169: This incident would not have occurred had the forklift operator been more aware of their surroundings when loading freight. A dunnage pallet should have been used to protect other freight from being punctured by the protruding metal on skid. The forklift operator was counselled and disciplined as a result of the incident. This incident may be used in future dock safety topics to illustrate the importance of proper freight handling practices.

The piping for the discharge valve has a sheer section on it designed to break off if impacted in an accident.  Our shop in Gary advised that it must have a crack in it as it was leaking when the driver attempted to unload it.  The crack is not visible but under pressure the leak was visible.  We had to transload the product in to a new trailer.
column169: The discharge piping did not appear to be impacted by anything that would have caused the crack.  There was no internal signs of corrosion or deterioration either.  We can only assume it was a stress crack that developed over time.  We have not seen any other units have this issue so there does not appear to be a trend to solve for.  We are going to monitor for trends going forward but this otherwise appears to be an isolated issue.

CHES driver picked up a load from the Biomarin facility, where the shipper packaged and loaded the truck.  Enroute to the designated facility, the truck was pulled into the Nimitz scale house for a routine inspection.  It was found a small amount of liquid spilled out of one container.  The chemist riding in the truck was able to cleanup the spill and overpack the leaking container.  CHES dispatched management to assess the package and cleanup procedures.  It was agreed upon by personnel and CHP that the cleanup and repackage was not compliant.
column169: An investigation was conducted and we learned BioMarin was not using the correct closure after filling the 5 gallon container.  It was also learned that while these containers go through a second set of in-site chemists (QC team), the incorrect closure was not identified.  Additional training will be required of the in-site chemists on manufacturer's closure instructions.  All personnel, to include drivers, in-site personnel and all chemists within the entire district will be trained on manufacturer's closure instructions so as to prevent recurrence.

column168: THIS IBC SHIPMENT WAS LOADED INTO ONE OF OUR TRAILERS SCHEDULED TO GO OUT FOR DELIVERY. WHEN THE DRIVER WAS READY TO LEAVE HE OBSERVED THAT A PLACARD HOLDER ON THE SIDE OF THE TRAILER WAS BROKEN AND NEEDED TO BE REPLACED. THE DRIVER TOOK THE TRAILER OVER TO OUR FLEET MAINTENANCE SHOP TO HAVE THE PLACARD HOLDER REPLACED. WHILE DOING SO THE FLEET MAINTENANCE TECHNICIAN DRILLED A HOLE THROUGH THE SIDE OF THE TRAILER TO MOUNT THE PLACARD HOLDER AND UNFORTUNATELY ALSO DRILLED THROUGH THE SIDE OF THE IBC THAT WAS STAGED IN THE TRAILER RIGHT NEXT TO WHERE HE HAD DRILLED THE HOLE. CONSEQUENTLY, THIS CAUSED THE UNINTENTIONAL RELAEASE. THE IBC WAS TEMPORAILY REPAIRED BY DRIVING A WOODEN DOWEL INTO THE HOLE AND THE CONTNENTS WAS EVENTUALLY TRANSFERRED TO A REPLACEMENT IBC AND DELIVERED TO THE ULTIMATE CONSIGNEE WITHOUT FURTHER INCIDENT.
column169: FLEET TECHNICIANS NEED TO BE AWARE OF THE CONTENTS OF THE STAGED FREIGHT IN TRAILERS BEFORE PERFORMING CERTAIN MAITNENANCE FUNCTIONS TO OPREVENT THESE TYPES OF UNINTENTIONAL RELEASES FROM OCCURRING.

column168: On 02/24/2022, at 1302 hours, personnel in the CSXT Marion Yard discovered GATX 90949, a loaded tank car of Potassium Hydroxide, leaking from the top of the car. The car was isolated and the shipper, National Response Center, and Ohio Environmental Protection Agency were notified.  (CHEMTREC Report #2022-0224-00190). Specialized Professional Services, Inc, a CSXT emergency response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found the manway cover was secured with all cover bolts, however there was no gasket present resulting in the release of lading during movement of the tank car. The issue was identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shipper Jeanne Kochevar of Ashta Chemicals, phone 440-997-6862. Contractor personnel installed a manway nozzle gasket, secured the manway cover, and decontaminated the car. The leak was secured and the car was released for transport. This incident did require a special switching move. 7.1 is not required.  Cause Code: 207 NARRI: 100

column168: AmeriGas propane bobtail failed to stop at a stop sign located at a 4 way intersection and then collided with a passenger vehicle.  The bobtail then struck a utility pole and overturned on its side.  As a result of this event a crack in the piping near an elbow just prior to the hose inlet occurred.  The driver of the bobtail went to the rear of the vehicle and closed the nearest valve upstream of the crack, stopping the release.  The time from the onset of the incident to the time that the valve was closed is estimated to have been less than 5 minutes.

column168: On the morning of 2/2/2022 at approximately 05:45am the seal was broken and door opened on trailer 286599L from SEFL Garland, TX SVC. The trailer was located in dock door 44 of the Baton Rouge, LA SVC. Immediately a large release of vapor exited from the trailer. The situation was assessed and determined that there were 4 M350 gallon tote tanks of Nitric Acid(Pro#761684204) on th6 trailer and one of them had visibly leaked out onto the floor of the trailer. Regional Safety was contacted immediately. Precautionary measures were initiated, the immediate area of the trailer was cleared, there was no active leak or release on the ground, absorbent boom was placed on the ground around the trailer just in case. Hazmat One was called and arrived at 08:30am. Hazmat One took over the situation with the SEFL QAL assisting. Totes were removed from the trailer one by one and checked to determine where the product release was coming from. The initial determination by Hazmat One was that tote DA0014 had a bad lid seal on top and product had sloshed from the top during transit. They repaired and replaced the seal accordingly. It was later determined that there was an additional problem with tote DA00988. The tote was still releasing vapor from the bottom of one of the legs. USES flushed the leg with a water/ soda ash solution, however the tote continued to release vapor and product. It was then determined that there's a hairline crack above the leg in the bottom of the tote which is not visible to the eye. LA State Police Hazmat& Hazmat One agreed to place the tank in a containment area and caution tape the area off, until a replacement tank was received the next day 02/03/2022 from Garland, TX in order to transfer the product. Due to in-climate weather in the Dallas Tx area on 02/03/2022, the tank was not received due to trucks not being able to transport. Univar Geismar, LA made arrangements for a rental tote in order to transfer the material.

At this time, the Borger yard was evacuated of all employees. PNR GM, Brynn Moreland then contacted CP Chem(destination user) to notify them of the findings. column168: GATX 92764 was observed leaking product from the protective housing in the PTRA North Yard. Slick Response Services was notified and responded to the scene where they found that product was pushing past the closed 3" liquid line valve and plug. Slick depressurized the tank car, opened the liquid valve to allow product to go back into the tank then closed the valve and applied teflon tape to the valve plug.  After securing the car the PTRA and Slick Response moved the car back and forth several times to see if ball valve was still leaking. Slick removed the plug and found product had again bypassed the valve. The plug was replaced and secured and the shipper was notified that the car would need to be returned to the facility under and OTMA and have the valve assembly inspected and or replaced.

column168: The RTS driver was almost finished being loaded at the customer and a very small drip was noticed on the belly of the tanker. Investigation determined that the barrel of the tanker was leaking under the insulation. The leak was very slow and PPG utilized a bucket to collect a total of approximately 1/4 gallon of the waste.  A second tanker was mobilized to the customer site. Load was transferred to the second tanker and transported to the destination facility.  The leaking tanker was taken out of service and is being sent to a certified tank repair facility to diagnose the location and extent of the leak. RTS may choose to either repair the tanker or permanently remove the tanker from service.
column169: All RTS tankers go through annual HM-183 testing. This release could be from a prior repair. IF that is the case we will be addressing the repair facility and making sure that they are proving the quality repairs that we demand.

column168: Package containing UN3260 was found and offered to the spill office at our Memphis hub location when it was seen the package was spilling a powdery substance. Inspection of the package found the fiberboard box contained plastic bottles filled with the commodity. While the bottle contained positive closure, the lid on the bottles is reported to have broke during transit and allowed for all contents to leak out. It was reported there were not barrier bags nor absorbent materials in the package with the bottle. Package placed in a salvage drum for containment. Part of a multi place shipment. Second box is being sought so both can be returned to shipper as FedEx policy does not allow for salvage drums to travel internationally.
